{"id":"1908.00285","submitter":"Sounak Sadhukhan","authors":"Sounak Sadhukhan and S. K. Basu","title":"Modeling Tumor Angiogenesis with Cellular Automata","comments":"the article is incomplete and it required major revision","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.TO physics.bio-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Angiogenesis is the formation of new blood vessels from the existing vessels.\nDuring tumour angiogenesis, tumour cells secret a number of chemical substrates\ncalled tumour angiogenic factors (TAFs). These factors diffuse through the\nextracellular matrix (ECM) and degrade the basement membrane of nearby\nvasculature. The TAFs also disrupt the corresponding endothelial cell receptors\nand form finger like capillary sprouts. These factors also create a chemical\ngradient (chemotaxis) between the tumour and the surrounding blood vessels. Due\nto the chemotactic force, the capillary sprouts migrate towards the tumour. On\nthe other hand, a haptotactic force generated due to fibronectin which is\nsecreted by the endothelial cell, also acts on these sprouts. These sprouts\ngrow through the proliferation of recruited endothelial cells from the parent\nvessels. Tumour angiogenesis is not fully understood yet. In this paper, we use\n2-D cellular automata (CA) model to study the behavior of tumour angiogenesis\nusing both Moore and von-Neumann neighborhood. The CA model also mimics\ncapillary sprout branching and the fusion of two adjacent sprout tips\n(anastomoses). In this simulation, a couple of important points are noted: a)\nno two capillary sprouts are generated from adjacent locations; b) as the\nsprouts approach closer to the tumour, its branching tendency increases; c)\nchemotaxis is the most effective driving force for angiogenesis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 1 Aug 2019 09:17:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 23 Sep 2019 16:24:42 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"W